@page "/docs/outline"
@using MudX.Docs.Outline
@using MudX.Docs.Examples

<PageTitle>Outline</PageTitle>

<DocsPage ApiJson="mudxoutline.api.json">
    <DocsPageHeader Title="Outline">
        <Description>
            A scrollspy control for displaying an index or table of contents on either side of the text content.
            Typically you would surround the document with <CodeInline>MudXOutline</CodeInline> and each individual
            section with <CodeInline>MudXOutlineSection</CodeInline>.
        </Description>
    </DocsPageHeader>

    <DocsPageSection Title="Basic Usage">
        <Description>
            The outline is a scrollspy control for displaying an index or table of contents on either side of the text content.
            The <CodeInline>MudXOutline</CodeInline> is a wrapper for a number of <CodeInline>MudXOutlineSection</CodeInline>'s.
            Each <CodeInline>MudXOutlineSection</CodeInline> has a <CodeInline Tag="false">Title</CodeInline> that is used for the index
            and whatever content is supplied inside is what is displayed in the main content area. By default the control
            requires very minimal setup, however to nest it inside another be sure to set the <CodeInline Tag="false">ScrollContainerSelector</CodeInline>
            to the outer element with a scrollbar as scrollspy will only work if a scrollbar is present. Remember when using the Selector to
            preface a class with a . or an id with a #.
        </Description>
        <ChildContent>
            <SectionContent Codes="@OutlineBasicExampleCode.Files">
                <OutlineBasicExample />
            </SectionContent>
        </ChildContent>
    </DocsPageSection>

    <DocsPageSection Title="Index Customization">
        <Description>
            There are many properties you can change to customize the look and feel of the control, but ultimately
            the content is strictly upon you to style and use. <CodeInline Tag="false">Anchor</CodeInline> and
            <CodeInline Tag="false">Width</CodeInline> are most common.
        </Description>
        <ChildContent>
            <SectionContent Codes="@OutlineCustomizeExampleCode.Files">
                <OutlineCustomizeExample />
            </SectionContent>
        </ChildContent>
    </DocsPageSection>

    <DocsPageSection Title="Scroll Style">
        <Description>
            You can customize the Variant used for the ScrollSpy by setting the <CodeInline Tag="false">StyleVariant</CodeInline>
            property. Available options are <CodeInline Tag="false">None</CodeInline>, <CodeInline Tag="false">Bullet</CodeInline>,
            <CodeInline Tag="false">Scroll</CodeInline> and <CodeInline Tag="false">Minimal</CodeInline>. Additionally,
            the default behavior of <CodeInline Tag="false">Underline</CodeInline> can be overridden by setting it to false.
        </Description>
        <ChildContent>
            <SectionContent Codes="@OutlineVariantExampleCode.Files">
                <OutlineVariantExample />
            </SectionContent>
        </ChildContent>
    </DocsPageSection>

    <DocsPageSection Title="Other Options">
        <Description>
            You can nest both <CodeInline>MudXOutline</CodeInline> and <CodeInline>MudXOutlineSection</CodeInline> components. The Table of Contents is displayed using 
            <CodeInline>MudPopover</CodeInline>, while scrollspy behavior is managed by JavaScript modules behind the scenes. You can also nest one 
            <CodeInline>MudXOutlineSection</CodeInline> inside another to create hierarchical sections in the Table of Contents that will indent 
            automatically up to five levels.
        </Description>
        <ChildContent>
            <SectionContent Codes="@OutlineNestingExampleCode.Files">
                <OutlineNestingExample />
            </SectionContent>
        </ChildContent>
    </DocsPageSection>

</DocsPage>

@code {
#pragma warning disable CS0414
    private static string __title__ = "Outline";
#pragma warning restore CS0414
}